<paragraph id="C225D6B2C9C9BA2A68B77E5940D8914F" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB93CBD62D4A26690E5FD64086E7709C" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The male is indistinguishable from the males of 
<taxonomicName id="1AC7D60041A947C353292AF9BE17AF89" genus="P." lsidName="P. flavipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="098FEAE48DF598FA7F418E4721341F90" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D488DE80A039ED3736EB4DDB8FF22B7F" genus="P." lsidName="P. mombasensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="mombasensis">
<emphasis id="3E62CF44EF3D0A919F65AF1B87E437EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. mombasensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by body shape and colouration, but its bulb is slightly narrower than in these species and the embolic spiral is tightly convoluted; width of the basal embolic loop equals only a half of tegulum width, whereas in both other species it is as wide as tegulum. The female can be separated from congeners in having copulatory ducts compactly arranged and not forming loose loops (see Fig. 
<figureCitation id="80489E0A2624B9C48DCB23C6A98CE3A6" captionStart="Figures 22–28" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 22 - 28. Pachyballus castaneus 22 cheliceral dentition 23 - 25 palpal organ, ventral view (24 specimen from Zimbabwe) 26 palpal organ, lateral view 27 epigyne 28 internal structure of epigyne." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures22-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427057" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">28</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="32EDD42CDFF9099382AA16E0F07A51E2" doi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures22-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427057" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" start="Figures 22–28" startId="F6">
<paragraph id="A5D7309CA7C97E47181673CC955A8864" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
